            <h3>Hypergraph-Based Image Segmentation</h3>
            <h4>Students: Darcy & Juan<br>Majors: Mathematics</h4>
            <p>During the summer of 2020, we had the opportunity to participate in the <a
                    href="https://science.osti.gov/wdts/vfp" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener external"
                    alt="(opens in new tab)">Visiting Faculty Program (VFP)</a> at Lawrence Berkeley National
                Laboratory. During this 10 week program, we worked under <a href="https://tperciano.wixsite.com/home"
                    target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener external" alt="(opens in new tab)">Talita Perciano</a> from
                the Data Analytics and Visualization research group at LBNL. I met Talita when I participated in the <a
                    href="http://shinstitute.org/srp-application/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener external"
                    alt="(opens in new tab)">Sustainable Research Pathways Workshop</a>. Although a virtual summer
                research program wasn't ideal, we still had a lot of fun learning about graph theory, image
                segmentation, and how to code in C++.</p>
            <p>This semester, both Darcy and Juan are supported by the Stan State <a
                    href="https://www.csustan.edu/office-research-sponsored-programs/sersca-program" target="_blank"
                    rel="noreferrer noopener external" alt="(opens in new tab)">SERSCA</a> program.
            </p>
            <a id="abstract">
                <p>Abstract: X-ray micro-tomography (&mu;-CT) is a non-destructive 3D imaging technique often used to
                    image material samples. The Advanced Light Source at Berkeley National Laboratory houses a
                    synchroton-based &mu;-CT instrument which produces high volumes of data at a fast rate. This has led
                    to the need for image processing techniques capable of extracting valuable information in large
                    complex data sets. Image segmentation is an important processing step which separates various
                    components in an image. Graph-based segmentation algorithms have been used for many years, with
                    current interest primarily in designing algorithms which can handle large data sets. Recent
                    approaches using Markov Random Fields (MRFs) exploit local properties of MRFs to run computations in
                    parallel. In this project, we developed an image segmentation algorithm using a hypergraph-based MRF
                    model. The algorithm is coded in C++ and preliminary results indicate that this generalized model
                    improves precision of the segmentation of &mu;-CT images. We still have a lot left to do, but we are
                    excited about the results so far!</p>
            </a>
        </article>
